A possible solution for this is to extend your custom rule constructor and pass the `$request` as a param.

CustomRule

```
namespace App\Rules;

use Illuminate\Contracts\Validation\Rule;
use Illuminate\Http\Request;

class CustomRule implements Rule
{
    protected $request;

    public function __construct(Request $request)
    {
        $this-&gt;request = $request;
    }
    
    public function passes($attribute, $value)
    {
        return ...;
    }
    
    ...
}
```

YourController
```
$request-&gt;validate([
    &#39;input1&#39; =&gt; [&#39;required&#39;, &#39;string&#39;, new CustomRule($request)],
    &#39;input2&#39; =&gt; [&#39;required&#39;, &#39;string&#39;],
]);
```

This was also discussed as an issue [Allow custom validation rules access all parameters](https://github.com/laravel/framework/issues/23094) in `laravel/framework`

