This happens usually in RTL direction apps, when the cell gets reused, it does not dismiss the position it had, in the cell before it

the solution is to always force UICollectionView to be flipped, every time the cell loads, using the collectionView&#39;s flow layout attribute `flipsHorizontallyInOppositeLayoutDirection` to return true,

1) Create a custom flow layout class with the following properties:

    class ArabicCollectionFlow: UICollectionViewFlowLayout {
        override func prepare() {
            super.prepare()
            self.scrollDirection = .horizontal
        }
        override var flipsHorizontallyInOppositeLayoutDirection: Bool {
            return true
        }
    }

in your Tableviewcell class, in `awakeFromNib` to make sure that the nib is loaded, ignoring the fact it was reused, you&#39;re going to set the collectionView flow layout to be the one we created above

    override func awakeFromNib() {
        super.awakeFromNib()
        categories.collectionViewLayout = ArabicCollectionFlow()
    }
Keep noted that this flow layout has to be set after your `reloadData`

Also, you may only need to use this solution if your app is running in RTL mode, so you can do your checks before using this custom layout

